# Cursor Rules — Branham Web App (Next.js + Supabase)

Project: **Branham Web App**

Purpose: A minimal, high-performance web app (ChatGPT-style UI) that manages:
- Auth and user sessions (Supabase)
- Chat session/history persistence (Supabase) for logged-in users
- Rendering model responses with **human-readable references**
- Making exactly **one downstream API call**: to the **Branham Model API** (Python service)

No reader view in v1 (references are rendered inline and in an expandable list).

---

## 0) Non-negotiables

- Use **Next.js best practices** to minimize latency and avoid common perf pitfalls.
- Keep the UI simple: chat window + history sidebar (ChatGPT-like).
- Supabase client is responsible for:
  - authentication (sign-in/sign-out/session)
  - chat history CRUD (logged-in users only)
- No caching in v1 (no response caching, no embedding caching).
- The web app makes **only one API call per user message**:
  - `POST /chat` to the Branham Model API
- Everything else is local UI work: parsing references, resolving metadata, rendering.

Free app v1 constraints:
- No API key management in v1.
- Support anonymous (not logged-in) usage:
  - user can chat
  - history is not persisted until user logs in
  - once logged in, persistence applies going forward

---

## 1) Performance principles (Next.js-specific)

Next.js can feel slower than direct React if misused. Follow these rules:

- Prefer **Server Components by default** (Next.js App Router), but keep the chat input + streaming message area as **Client Components**.
- Avoid heavy client-side bundles:
  - keep dependencies minimal
  - do not import large libraries into client components
  - use dynamic import for non-critical UI widgets
- Use **streaming UI**:
  - stream tokens from Model API to the frontend via the backend route handler
  - update the assistant message progressively
- Use stable rendering patterns:
  - avoid re-rendering the whole message list for each token
  - append tokens to a single message state efficiently
- Keep database round-trips minimal:
  - batch queries (e.g., fetch references metadata for all citations in one query)
  - avoid per-reference queries in a loop

---

## 2) App behavior overview

### 2.1 User story (anonymous + logged-in)
1. User opens app.
2. User may use the app without logging in (anonymous mode):
   - can send messages
   - receives answers
   - session exists only in local state (memory / local storage optional)
   - no Supabase history persistence
3. If user logs in:
   - new chats and messages are persisted (Supabase)
   - existing anonymous chat may optionally be offered for “Save this chat” (optional UX; not required v1)
4. User sends a message.
5. Web backend sends exactly one request to Model API:
   - `POST /chat`
6. UI streams and renders the response.
7. UI parses references like:
   - `[47-0412--M: ¶2–¶3]`
8. UI resolves `date_id` → sermon title and displays references in plain language:
   - “Faith Is The Substance (12-04-47, Morning), paragraphs 2–3”
9. For logged-in users, all messages and references are saved in Supabase.

---

## 3) Data modeling and history behavior (Supabase)

### 3.1 Relationships (LOCKED)
- `chat_sessions` has a **one-to-many** relationship with `chat_messages`.
- History sidebar is built by querying chat sessions for the user, then showing:
  - session title (or auto-generated)
  - last updated time
- Chat view is built by querying messages for a selected session:
  - `SELECT * FROM chat_messages WHERE session_id = ... ORDER BY created_at ASC`

### 3.2 Anonymous mode rules
- Anonymous user has:
  - no `user_id`
  - no DB persistence
- In anonymous mode:
  - messages exist only in local UI state
  - session_id can be generated locally (uuid) for frontend organization
- On login:
  - new messages are persisted under the user
  - optional: migrate anonymous session into a real chat session (not required v1)

---

## 4) Reference parsing and rendering (LOCKED UX requirement)

Model will return references in text, e.g.:
- `[47-0412--M: ¶2–¶3]`

The web app must:
- Parse these reference tokens reliably.
- Render them in a more human-friendly format using metadata from DB:
  - sermon title (from DB)
  - date_id (canonical)
  - paragraph range in plain language

### 4.1 Parsing rules
- Pattern conceptually:
  - `[` + `date_id` + `:` + paragraph range + `]`
- Extract:
  - `date_id` = `dd-mm-yy--M|E`
  - `paragraph_start`, `paragraph_end`
- Be tolerant:
  - `¶2–¶3` or `¶2-¶3`
  - allow spaces

### 4.2 Metadata resolution
- The app stores `sermon_metadata` mapping:
  - `date_id -> title, preacher, language(optional)`
- On rendering an assistant message:
  - collect all `date_id`s found in that message
  - fetch metadata in one query (batch)
  - render a references panel/list

### 4.3 references_json (LOCKED)
- Keep `references_json` column on `chat_messages` (jsonb).
- When storing an assistant message, store both:
  - raw assistant text
  - parsed structured references (references_json)
- On render:
  - prefer references_json for speed and stability
  - parsing raw text is fallback only

---

## 5) Supabase responsibilities (v1)

Supabase client handles:
- Auth
- Session state
- Chat history persistence for logged-in users

No caching in v1.

### 5.1 Required database tables (minimum)

#### chat_sessions
- id (uuid, PK)
- user_id (uuid, nullable for future; in v1 persisted sessions require user_id)
- title (text, optional auto-title)
- created_at
- updated_at

Notes:
- For logged-in users: `user_id` is required.
- Anonymous sessions should not be persisted in v1.

#### chat_messages
- id (uuid, PK)
- session_id (uuid, FK -> chat_sessions.id)
- user_id (uuid, nullable; in v1 persisted messages require user_id)
- role (`user` | `assistant`)
- content (text)
- created_at
- references_json (jsonb, optional but strongly recommended)

Notes:
- One session has many messages.
- Message order is by created_at ascending.

#### sermon_metadata
- date_id (text, PK)
- title (text)
- preacher (text, default “William Marrion Branham”)
- language (text, default “en”)
- created_at

Notes:
- sermon_metadata is pre-seeded from corpus pipeline.
- The app uses this table to resolve `date_id` → human title.

---

## 6) API call contract (web app side)

### 6.1 Single downstream call per message (LOCKED)
The app backend calls the Model API:

- `POST {MODEL_API_BASE_URL}/chat`

Request:
- session_id
- user_language
- query
- optional:
  - history_window
  - conversation_summary

Important v1 change:
- **No conversation summarization** in v1.
- Use truncation instead:
  - send only the last N messages or last X tokens as `history_window`
  - keep it deterministic and fast

Response:
- answer
- mode
- references (structured list)
  - date_id
  - paragraph_start
  - paragraph_end
  - chunk_ids

### 6.2 Web backend route
Implement a single Next.js route handler:
- `POST /api/chat`

Responsibilities:
- Determine if user is logged in (Supabase session):
  - if logged in: persist session/message history
  - if anonymous: do not persist, but still allow chat
- Insert user message into DB only if logged in
- Call Model API (streaming)
- Persist assistant message + references_json only if logged in
- Return streamed response to client

---

## 7) UI requirements (ChatGPT-like)

### 7.1 Layout
- Left sidebar:
  - list of chat sessions (history) (logged-in only)
  - create new chat button
  - sign in / sign out button
- Main panel:
  - messages list
  - message input box
  - streaming assistant response
  - references display for assistant messages

Anonymous UX:
- Sidebar can be hidden or show a “Sign in to save history” banner.
- Chat works normally but is not persisted.

### 7.2 Behavior
- Logged-in:
  - New chat creates a `chat_sessions` row
  - Sending message creates `chat_messages` row for user
  - Assistant message saved at end of stream with references_json
- Anonymous:
  - New chat is local-only
  - Sending message updates local state only
  - Assistant message stored in local state only

### 7.3 Accessibility
- Keyboard navigation for sessions list
- Enter to send, Shift+Enter for newline
- Good contrast and readable typography

---

## 8) Next.js codebase structure (recommended scaffold)

web-app/
- README.md
- next.config.js
- .env.local
- src/
  - app/
    - layout.tsx
    - page.tsx
    - (auth)/
      - login/page.tsx
    - (app)/
      - chat/page.tsx
      - chat/[sessionId]/page.tsx
    - api/
      - chat/route.ts          # the ONLY model API call path
  - components/
    - chat/
      - ChatShell.tsx
      - MessageList.tsx
      - MessageBubble.tsx
      - Composer.tsx
      - ReferencesPanel.tsx
      - ReferencePill.tsx
      - SessionSidebar.tsx
      - AnonymousBanner.tsx
    - auth/
      - AuthGate.tsx
  - lib/
    - supabase/
      - client.ts
      - server.ts
      - middleware.ts
    - modelApi/
      - client.ts              # fetch/stream wrapper
    - references/
      - parse.ts               # parse [date_id: ¶x–¶y]
      - resolve.ts             # batch resolve date_ids -> metadata
      - format.ts              # format references in plain language
    - db/
      - queries.ts             # typed DB access helpers
    - utils/
      - ids.ts
      - time.ts
      - safeHtml.ts
  - styles/
    - globals.css

---

## 9) Streaming implementation rules (important)

- Use `ReadableStream` and incremental decoding on client.
- Keep assistant message state localized:
  - avoid re-rendering entire list per token
  - append to the current assistant message only
- Persist only after completion (logged-in only):
  - write the final assistant content + references_json once stream ends
- Do not store partial messages in DB in v1 (keep DB clean and simple).

---

## 10) Security and rate limiting (v1 minimal)

- Validate Supabase auth session for persistence actions.
- Anonymous requests are allowed but rate-limited (simple server-side limit).
- No API key management in v1.
- Never expose Model API keys to the client.
- Store minimal PII.

---

## 11) What is intentionally out of scope for v1

- Full sermon reader view (deep linking into text)
- Caching layer
- Offline support
- Advanced analytics dashboards
- Multi-tenant admin console

These can be added after v1 is stable.
